title: US Indexes Close With Gains on the Last Day of 2020
text: The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at 30,606.48 on Thursday with a gain of 196.92 points or 0.65%. The S&P 500 closed at 3,756.07 for a gain of 24.03 points or 0.64%.

title: REITs In 2020: Good, Bad, And Ugly
text: U.S. equity markets finished an unforgettable 2020 at record highs despite the unprecedented ongoing global pandemic, rallying back from a historic market sell-off that pushed financial markets to the absolute brink. Finishing the year with returns of 17.6%, the S&P 500 finished higher by 1.3% on the final week. Despite the reopening-rebound, Mid-Caps and Small-Caps lagged on the week and for 2020.

title: So Far, The Bulls Are Disappointed In 'Santa'
text: With the "Santa Claus" rally wrapping up next week, we are maintaining our long bias with reduced hedges at the moment. We made no changes to our portfolio mix during the past week except for adding a 5% weight of SPY to our current holdings.

title: Main Street Catches Up To Wall Street
text: Profitable investing will shift from reliance on excess liquidity to economic growth/corporate profits and cash flow. We see the shift from Wall Street to Main Street in 2021/2022 benefitting those companies leveraged to a sustainable global economic recovery.

title: S&P 500 Weekly Update: What A Year
text: The quickest 30% drop in market history led to the shortest bear market followed by the quickest recovery on record. The S&P, Nasdaq, and the Dow 30 post new highs as 2020 comes to a close. Global markets follow the "new high" trend.

title: S&P 500 Concentration Risk Could Define 2021
text: Company and sector weightings in the S&P 500 reflect current valuation, not economic impact. Currently SPY is concentrated in a small number of companies trading at extremely high valuations. Recent positive performance has been driven by a small number of stocks.
